    <section xml:id="SECTIONhyperb-trig-hang">
      <title>Hyperbolic Trigonometry: The Hanging Chain</title>

      <p>
        We commented in <xref ref="SECTIONbridg-chains-telesc">Section</xref> that Galileo
        believed erroneously that a chain hanging from two pegs falls
        naturally into the shape of a parabola. In
        <xref ref="PROBLEMcatenary">Problem</xref> we showed that Galileo was wrong but we
        have not
        yet addressed the question: What is the shape of a hanging chain?
      </p>
      <p>

        Recall that the hanging chain must satisfy the differential
        equation
        <me>
          \dfdxn{y}{x}{2} = \frac{w}{H}\sqrt{1+\left(\dfdx{y}{x}\right)^2}
        </me>
        where <m>w</m> is the weight density of the chain and <m>H</m> is the
        (constant) magnitude of the horizontal tension. In
        <xref ref="PROBLEMHangingChain">Problem</xref> we will see that although the
        natural exponential function <m>y=e^x</m> is not the solution itself,
        it is the key to the solution.
      </p>

      <problem  xml:id="PROBLEMHangingChain">
        <title>The Shape of a Hanging Chain</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            The Calculus in this problem is pretty straightforward but the
            Algebra gets a bit messy. To avoid some of this mess in <xref ref="PROBLEMHangChainA"> part</xref>, <xref ref="PROBLEMHangChainB"> part</xref>, and <xref ref="PROBLEMHangChainC"> part</xref> we will solve the special case where <m>\frac{w}{H}=1</m>
            in  <xref ref="PROBLEMHangChainD"> part</xref> we<rsq/>ll use our solution of this special case to solve
            the original problem.
          </p>
          <p>
            So assume that <m>\frac{w}{H}=1</m>.  For this special case we will call
            our variables <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>, rather than <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>. The reasons for
            this will become clear in  <xref ref="PROBLEMHangChainD"> part</xref>.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task  xml:id="PROBLEMHangChainA">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Show that
              <m>1+\left(\frac{e^X-e^{-X}}{2}\right)^2=\left(\frac{e^X+e^{-X}}{2}\right)^2.</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <hint>
            <p>
              It might help to make the substitution <m>e^X=a</m> just to make
              things <q>easier on the eyes.</q> That makes <m>e^{-X}=\frac1a.</m>
            </p>
          </hint>
        </task>
        <task  xml:id="PROBLEMHangChainB">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Show that
              <me>\dfdx{\left(\frac12\left(e^X+e^{-X}\right)\right)}{X} =\frac12 \left(e^X-e^{-X}\right) </me>
              and that
              <me>\dfdx{\left(\frac12\left(e^X-e^{-X}\right)\right)}{X} =\frac12 \left(e^X+e^{-X}\right). </me>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task  xml:id="PROBLEMHangChainC">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Show that the curve <m>Y=\frac12 \left( e^X+e^{-X}\right) </m>
              satisfies the differential equation
              <me>\dfdxn{Y}{X}{2}=\sqrt{1+\left(\dfdx{Y}{X} \right)^2 }.</me>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task  xml:id="PROBLEMHangChainD">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Now let<rsq/>s tackle the original problem.
              Show that
              <men  xml:id="EQUATIONCatSol">
                y=\frac{H}{w}
                \left(\frac{e^{\frac{wx}{H}}+e^{-\frac{wx}{H}}}{2}\right)
              </men>
              satisfies the equation
              <me>
                \dfdxn{y}{x}{2}=\frac{w}{H} \sqrt{1+\left(\dfdx{y}{x}\right)^2}
              </me>
              where <m>w</m> is the weight density of the chain, and <m>H</m> is the
              constant (magnitude of the) horizontal tension.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <hint>
            <p>
              This is essentially the same computation you did for the
              special case, but the Algebra is messier. Consider making
              it <q>easier on the eyes</q> with the
              substitutions <me>X=\frac{wx}{H}</me> and
              <me>Y(X)=\frac12\left(e^X+e^{-X}\right).</me>
              We already know from <xref ref="PROBLEMHangChainC">part</xref> that
              <m>\dfdxn{Y}{X}{2}=\sqrt{1+\left(\dfdx{Y}{X}\right)^2}</m>.
              Notice that <m>y=\frac{H}{w}Y(X)</m> and use this to show that
              <m>
                \dfdx{y}{x}=\dfdx{Y}{X}\text{ and that }
                \dfdxn{y}{x}{2}=\frac{w}{H}\dfdxn{Y}{X}{2}.
              </m>
            </p>
          </hint>
        </task>
        <task  xml:id="PROBLEMHangChainE">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Assume that <m>w=1 </m>, and <m>H=1</m> and graph the curve given in
              <xref ref="EQUATIONCatSol"></xref>. Does it look like a hanging chain? What
              happens to the graph if we use <m>w=1</m> and <m>H=2</m>, or
              <m>w=2</m> and <m>H=1</m>? Does this make sense physically? Why or why
              not?
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
      </problem>

