      <p>
        When he designed the Gateway Arch in St. Louis, Missouri, architect <url
        href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eero_Saarinen"
        visual="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eero_Saarinen">Eero
        Saarinen</url> wanted to build it in the shape of an inverted
        catenary.  The arch would have a height of <m>630</m> feet and a
        width of <m>630</m> feet.  Its cross sections would be equilateral
        triangles with sides <m>54</m> feet at ground level shrinking to
        <m>17</m> feet at the top.  To obtain the shape of the arch,
        Saarinen decided that the centers of the triangular cross sections
        should follow the curve
        <men  xml:id="EQUATIONGatewayArch1">
          y=693.8597-68.7672 \cosh(.0100333 x),
        </men>
        where <m>
        -299.226\leq x\leq 299.226</m>.
