      <p>
        The simplest use to which we can put a <term>natural logarithm</term> is to
        aid in solving an equation like:
        <me>
          3^x=17.
        </me>
        The difficulty here is that the variable <m>x</m> is in the exponent so to
        isolate it we have to <q>undo</q> an exponential. This is exactly
        what logarithms do!  By Property #6, <m>\ln(3^x)=x\ln(3)</m>, so we can
        solve our equation like this:
        <md>
          <mrow>
            3^x\amp=17
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \ln(3^x)\amp = \ln(17)
          </mrow>
          <mrow> x\ln(3)\amp= \ln(17)\\</mrow>
          <mrow> x\amp=\frac{\ln(17)}{\ln(3)}.</mrow>
        </md>

        At this point we can use technology to find that
        <m>\ln(17) \approx 2.8332</m> and <m>\ln(3)\approx1.0986</m> so that
        <m>x=\frac{\ln(17)}{\ln(3)}\approx2.5789</m>.
      </p>

