      <p>
        The length of time that it takes for a quantity of a radioactive
        isotope to decay by one-half is called the <term>half-life</term> of the isotope.
        Each substance has its own half-life.
        The half-life for Carbon-14 is roughly <m>5,730</m> years; for Fluorine-18,
        it is <m>110</m> minutes; for Potassium-<m>40</m>, it is <m>1.25</m> billion years.
      </p>
      <aside>
<title>Comment</title>
        <p>
          In fact, all
          substances have a half-life. But some half-lives are more useful than others.
        </p>
      </aside>


