<section xml:id="SECTIONDerivNatLog">
<title>The Derivative of the Natural Logarithm</title>

<p>
  Since the <term>natural logarithm</term> is the inverse of the <term>natural
  exponential</term> we can find its derivative using the same trick that we
  used to find the derivatives of the inverse trig functions.  Start
  with the identity from Logarithm Property #1:
  <men xml:id="EQUATIONUseProp1">e^{\ln(x)} =x </men>
  and  make this easier on our eyes with the substitution
  <m>y=\ln(x)</m>. Differentiating <xref ref="EQUATIONUseProp1">equation</xref>
  we see that
  <me> e^y\dx{y}  = \dx{x}</me>.
  Thus
  <me>\dx{y} =\frac{1}{e^y}\dx{x}</me>.
  Once more making the  substitution <m>y=\ln(x)</m>  we have
  <me>  \dx{y} =\frac{1}{e^{\ln(x)}}\dx{x}</me>,
  and since <m>e^{\ln(x)}=x</m> we have
  <me>  \dx{y} =\frac{1}{x}\dx{x}</me>.
  <me>  \dx{y} =\frac{1}{x}\dx{x}</me>
  <men  xml:id="EQUATIONNatLogDeriv1"> \dx{(\ln(x))}  =x^{-1} \dx{x}.</men>
  <xref ref="EQUATIONNatLogDeriv1">equation</xref> is the last differentiation rule you
  need to memorize. Memorize it.
</p>

<p>
  As always the difficulty here is not remembering what the
  differentiation rule is, the difficulty is in learning to use it in
  tandem with all of the other rules. So practice is required. Lots of
  practice.
</p>


