<!--            <xref ref="EQUATIONDampedProblem1"></xref>. -->
<!--          \item Show that <m>y_2(t)</m> is also a solution of -->
<!--            <xref ref="EQUATIONDampedProblem1"></xref>. -->
<!--          \item Show that if <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are constants then -->
<!--            <m>w(t)=ay_1(t)+by_2(t)</m> -->
<!--            is also a solution of <xref ref="EQUATIONDampedProblem1"></xref>. -->
<!--         \end{enumerate} -->
<!-- \end{embeddedproblem} -->



<p>
  To find meaning in his solutions he returned to the simpler
  <xref ref="EQUATIONSHO6">equation</xref>,
  <me>  m\dfdxn{y}{t}{2}= -ky,</me> which he
  already knew how to solve. To make things simpler still he assumed
  that <m>m=k=1</m> and tried his crazy guess, <m>y=e^{ct}</m> again on
  <men  xml:id="EQUATIONEulerSimpleSHO-1">
    \dfdxn{y}{t}{2}= -y.
</men>
</p>
<problem xml:id="PROBLEMDampedOscillation1">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Show that <m>y=e^{ct}</m> is a solution of the differential
      <xref ref="EQUATIONEulerSimpleSHO-1">equation</xref> when <m>c=i</m> or <m>c=-i</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</problem>
<p>

  <xref ref="PROBLEMDampedOscillation1"></xref> shows that <m>y=e^{it}</m> and
  <m>y=e^{-it}</m> are both solutions of
  <xref ref="EQUATIONEulerSimpleSHO-1">equation</xref>,
  but Euler knew (as we do, see
  <xref ref="SECTIONmore-high-deriv"></xref>.) that the solution of
  <xref ref="EQUATIONEulerSimpleSHO-1">equation</xref> is
  <m>
    y(t)=a\cos(t)+b\sin(t)
</m>
where <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are constants.
</p>
<p>

  He now had  very different looking solutions of
  <xref ref="EQUATIONEulerSimpleSHO-1">equation</xref>. Euler guessed that somehow
  these  must be the same, so he set
  <me>
    e^{it}=a\cos(t)+b\sin(t)
</me>
and tried to find <m>a</m> and
<m>b</m>.
</p>

<problem xml:id="PROBLEMEulersFormula">
  <introduction>
    <p>
</p>
</introduction>
<task>
  <statement>
    <p>
Show that if <m>e^{it}=a\cos(t)+b\sin(t),</m> then <m>a=1</m> and <m>b=i.</m>
</p>
</statement>
<hint>
<p>
To get <m>a,</m> substitute <m>t=0.</m> To get <m>b,</m> differentiate
first.
</p>
</hint>
</task>
<task>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Show that if <m>e^{-it}=a\cos(t)+b\sin(t),</m> then <m>a=1</m> and
<m>b=-i.</m>
</p>
</statement>
</task>
</problem>
<!-- \begin{embeddedproblem-enumerate} -->
